    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_552620902" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/552620902" />
    <a title="Karla" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2846441-karla"><img alt="Karla" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1537371209p2/2846441.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/552620902?book_show_action=true">Mar 05, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karla" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karla" href="/user/show/2846441-karla">Karla</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer552620902" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11872551724171750818">I&apos;m definitely not qualified to say this is the best single volume treatment of Grant&apos;s life (I doubt anyone could agree on which book gets that honor), but it certainly was admirably thorough without becoming obsessively minute about trivial details. Brands knows which research to keep in the final draft, and he doesn&apos;t go far afield for that word-count suckage called &quot;unnecessary context,&quot; which seems to infest so much historical nonfiction nowadays.<br/><br/>Grant is probably one of the most likable mi</span>
  <span id="freeText11872551724171750818" style="display:none">I'm definitely not qualified to say this is the best single volume treatment of Grant's life (I doubt anyone could agree on which book gets that honor), but it certainly was admirably thorough without becoming obsessively minute about trivial details. Brands knows which research to keep in the final draft, and he doesn't go far afield for that word-count suckage called "unnecessary context," which seems to infest so much historical nonfiction nowadays.<br><br>Grant is probably one of the most likable military figures to come out of the Civil War era, at least for me, and that opinion became far more entrenched after reading Brands' book. Prior to this, he was a Civil War general first and a scandal-ridden president second. The bumpy spots of his administration seem to be all that's generally known of Grant's post-war legacy. But as Brands repeatedly states, he was a great, if flawed, human being; probably the most socially progressive president of the nineteenth century. (At least in his own heart. Gettin' shit done for and doing justice to anyone of dusky hue in those days was an uphill struggle.)<br><br>Even though he fought the war with no firm opinion on whether slavery was right or wrong, when it became an undeniable and valuable factor of the war, he treated the runaways and freedmen soldiers well and put far higher value on their abilities than many others in command did. After the war was over, he supported the efforts to guarantee equal civil rights and when he was president, he took measures to beat back the rapidly violent Klan activities. He wanted to heal the nation and keep it healed, but he wasn't inclined to sacrifice principle for the sake of appeasement.<br><br>His attitude towards Native Americans was similarly at odds with the general prejudices of the times. Far from parroting Sheridan's quote of "The only good Indian is a dead Indian," Grant tried to stall the Black Hills land rush as long as he could and personally negotiated with the Sioux chiefs to minimize bloodshed. (Custer really screwed that up.) Grant's fault lay in being in the wrong century, and his own personal distaste for protracted political fights, of which civil rights and Indian affairs were by default bitter and brutal.<br><br>His final years are really heartbreaking - financially ruined, emaciated by throat cancer and racing death's clock to finish his memoirs so his wife wouldn't have to worry about money after he was gone.<br><br>My fangirling for him knows no bounds, but I know he would receive it with his customary embarrassed modesty.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1380412124ra/810329.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>Overall, the political, military and personal biographies were evenly balanced, and the initial years of the Gilded Age were well-explored and defined. At no point did I ever feel lost, but nor did I feel bored hearing about things with which I was already acquainted. I'd definitely pick up another one of Brands' books.<br><br>(I'm marking off one star for the unabridged audiobook version. The reader was really annoying in his cadence and limited tones.)</span>
  <a data-text-id="11872551724171750818" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


