    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_439898382" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/439898382" />
    <a title="Cora" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1932455-cora"><img alt="Cora" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546328372p2/1932455.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/439898382?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cora" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cora" href="/user/show/1932455-cora">Cora</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1932455-cora?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer439898382" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3462696039141685990">Ulysses S. Grant was once one of the most popular men in America, and reading THE MAN WHO SAVED THE UNION, it&apos;s not hard to figure out why. It&apos;s not just his historic role as the general who led the Northern forces to victory in the Civil War. Grant was apparently just a likable, quietly charismatic person, and H.W. Brands is best when he is bringing that aspect to life. From his laconic self-deprecating reflections on the Mexican War (including one funny recollection about leading a heroic char</span>
  <span id="freeText3462696039141685990" style="display:none">Ulysses S. Grant was once one of the most popular men in America, and reading THE MAN WHO SAVED THE UNION, it's not hard to figure out why. It's not just his historic role as the general who led the Northern forces to victory in the Civil War. Grant was apparently just a likable, quietly charismatic person, and H.W. Brands is best when he is bringing that aspect to life. From his laconic self-deprecating reflections on the Mexican War (including one funny recollection about leading a heroic charge against what turned out to be an American position) to his self-possession even when battling terminal cancer, Grant emerges in this biography as a very appealing figure.<br /><br />Grant's reputation as president, once abysmal, has been on the upswing recently, and for good reason. For the near century from Lincoln's assassination to Kennedy's, only Grant took vigorous, principled action to defend the civil rights of black Americans and defeat groups like the Ku Klux Klan and the White League. Similarly, Grant supported a "peace policy" for American Indians that would preserve large parts of the West for the Native Americans (where, to be sure, they would be encouraged to adopt Christianity and white culture more generally), as opposed to many prominent Americans who believed in aggressive expansionism and killing any Indian who stood in their way.<br /><br />(Grant's presidency is generally associated with widespread corruption, of course, but this seems a little unfair. Many members of the Lincoln administration were also corrupt, and during the Civil War many Republican congressmen received kickbacks from railroad companies for their support of the transcontinental railroad. The Thirteenth Amendment, the purchase of Alaska from Russia, and the not guilty verdict in Andrew Johnson's impeachment trial were all secured by bribery on a massive scale. Singling Grant's administration out for being particularly corrupt seems unfair, when corruption was endemic in the politics of the era.)<br /><br />The problem is that while Grant seems more appealing than your average Gilded Age politician, his presidency was in large part a failure. Not long into Grant's second term, a financial crisis produced a grinding depression that would last for nearly a decade. Grant ignored calls to intervene in the crisis and later promoted wrong-headed austerity measures, almost certainly making the depression worse. The Depression, in turn, crushed northern support for Reconstruction efforts (IIRC Eric Foner makes that argument in RECONSTRUCTION), and Republicans after Grant generally abandoned African Americans to their long twilight struggle against racist terrorism and (later) oppressive Jim Crow laws. Meanwhile, Grant's Indian policy began to fall apart while he was still in office, when gold was discovered in the Black Hills which had been promised to the Sioux. Eventually most of the Indian land would fall into white hands.<br /><br />Brands is light on historical analysis as you might expect from a popular biography, and there were times when his judgments struck me as a little simplistic or flat out unconvincing. (Faced with Grant's larger failures, Brands often resorts to an "at least he tried" defense, which cuts no ice with me.) Also, the Civil War sections often suffered for lack of adequate maps, making it hard to understand specific battlefield tactics at times (for those who don't have the terrain of Vicksburg memorized, that is). But in general Brands tells the story of U.S. Grant with energy and brings the man to life.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3462696039141685990" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


