<div id="review_939277816" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/939277816" />
    <a title="David Bird" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11658189-david-bird"><img alt="David Bird" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/939277816?book_show_action=true">May 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David Bird" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David Bird" href="/user/show/11658189-david-bird">David Bird</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer939277816" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11143216897273972514">For an account of his Civil War years, Grant&apos;s own memoirs are unlikely to be bettered. But Brands does a good job with his life as a whole. He manages to admire his subject without being ostentatiously hagiographic. <br/><br/>As the war years are so familiar, the greater interest for me was in the coverage of Grant&apos;s period of service under Andrew Johnson, and then as President himself. Lincoln&apos;s greatness is further highlighted in contrast to the use that his successor attempted to make of Grant to shor</span>
  <span id="freeText11143216897273972514" style="display:none">For an account of his Civil War years, Grant's own memoirs are unlikely to be bettered. But Brands does a good job with his life as a whole. He manages to admire his subject without being ostentatiously hagiographic. <br /><br />As the war years are so familiar, the greater interest for me was in the coverage of Grant's period of service under Andrew Johnson, and then as President himself. Lincoln's greatness is further highlighted in contrast to the use that his successor attempted to make of Grant to shore up his own popularity. <br /><br />Brands argues, less forcefully than he might have, that Grant's reputation as among the worst of Presidents is the unjust result of his efforts to support African-American rights in the South. Lincoln's reputation, after all, has been aided by his death at the moment of victory. Reconstruction, particularly in the conflict between the rights of former slaves and the hegemony the former masters sought to reimpose was bound to be unpopular as any policy with winners and losers. The rights of the poor and powerless were easily offered in sacrifice to the altar of reconciliation. As Brands writes, <blockquote>The Southern Democrats forgot that secession was about slavery, the recast the Civil War as a difference over states' rights, and they recalled Reconstruction as a carnival of corruption from which they had at length redeemed the South. The Northern capitalist Republicans lost touch with the anti-slavery roots of their party, they pushed aside Lincoln in favor of J.P. Morgan and company, and if they didn't actively embrace the Southern redefinition of the war and its aftermath, they didn't bother to dispute it.</blockquote><br />In a sense, the retroactive tarnish of Grant's administrations is the inverse of the glow accorded to Ronald Reagan: much less about the actual deeds than about the ideological use. Brands book represents a solid and sober return to fact for assessment of the 18th President.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11143216897273972514" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

