    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_593756172" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/593756172" />
    <a title="Zachary" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3196101-zachary"><img alt="Zachary" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1467518658p2/3196101.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/593756172?book_show_action=true">Apr 18, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zachary" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zachary" href="/user/show/3196101-zachary">Zachary</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer593756172" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3816229122735863372">This book is an odd duck. It is quite readable, but it is absolutely not compelling. It took me a long time to get through because at no time did I feel I simply had to keep reading. It is also broad, providing a global view of Grant&apos;s life and times, but at the same time it is very shallow. Little is lingered on or examined in full. You get only broad strokes without a sense of the underlying details, and thereby no insight into what led to events and changes. This is particularly true of Grant</span>
  <span id="freeText3816229122735863372" style="display:none">This book is an odd duck. It is quite readable, but it is absolutely not compelling. It took me a long time to get through because at no time did I feel I simply had to keep reading. It is also broad, providing a global view of Grant's life and times, but at the same time it is very shallow. Little is lingered on or examined in full. You get only broad strokes without a sense of the underlying details, and thereby no insight into what led to events and changes. This is particularly true of Grant himself. I come away from the book with no new understanding. Had I just read this book, he would simply be a cipher. Brands doesn't give us psychological insight or motivations or anything like that. Grant had a particular mode of command and a particular approach to the presidency, but why? What was his thinking? How did he reach that thinking? Yes, part of this problem is that Grant was a cipher. He was not a very introspective or complicated person, and he left little behind to really explain himself or to give others insight into himself. (Largely, I think because he felt his actions explained himself.) This is true. Grant therefore makes for a difficult nut for a historian to crack. He is hard. But that is no excuse for a historian to not try, and therein lies my issue with this book. Brands is a good writer, and he churns out serviceable biographies of great people, but his books seldom delight a reader or give them a better understanding of the person. He is not a good historian. He is lazy and his analysis shallow because he just doesn't put forth the effort to achieve depth. And that problem is all the more acute when the subject of one of his biographies is a man like Ulysses S. Grant.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3816229122735863372" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


